Latin America in the Fight against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented magnitude and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not confront the crisis resolutely, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political responses in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health their top priority.
Others, unfortunately, downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, gave their citizens false information, and ignored not only scientific research but also the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders chose, in the midst of the tragedy, a populist and divisive policy.
Latin America's top priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily using vacant infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
In addition, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other important resources, and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) - in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump and his reckless decision to freeze about 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines - in order to finally end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has the domestic production in Latin America been interrupted, but the countries there also suffer from declining export volumes and prices, income losses from the lack of tourism and fewer foreign remittances, as well as strong capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the drop in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, bold measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who have no access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for companies are also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and related labor costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a quick economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of bankruptcies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system – and with it the entire national economy – would be endangered.
Many companies, particularly small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax deferrals, payment postponements, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees from governments to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Well-capitalized and managed state banks can also play a leading role in this.
Generally speaking, measures will vary from country to country, but overall, extraordinary fiscal resources will probably be required everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activity without worsening the risks to health.
The problem is that fiscal space in Latin America today is even narrower than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Therefore, fiscal burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
However, there is a risk of a downgrade in creditworthiness, which can be reduced by the governments' commitment to correct the higher fiscal deficits within a reasonable timeframe.
However, especially for the smaller and less developed Latin American countries, urgent external support for households and balance of payments is needed.
If both private companies and states incur higher deficits, the countries' current account balances are likely to deteriorate as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets - one of the greatest reversals in the modern history of financial markets - further exacerbate the problem.
The resulting currency depreciations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
It must take care of the short-term currency and budgetary needs of countries and continue to support economies in this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
To do this, it needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a revival of the IMF's global reserve currency - the Special Drawing Rights, which should reach a volume of one trillion SDR.
Although SDRs are allocated to member countries according to their IMF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the supervision of the Fund.
In addition, the IMF could create the necessary capacity by immediately doubling the volume of the new credit arrangements to cover the upcoming strong credit demand.
Finally, the Fund must improve access to low-threshold instruments with rapid disbursement - such as its Rapid Financing Instrument - or launch new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs are not approved in a timely manner.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps - either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Domestically, central banks must use all available instruments at their disposal and create new ones if necessary to supply the financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
Finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to provide further household support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official lending could be supplemented by a debt relief.
The MEB should also provide countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of the COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
Time plays a decisive role here.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is unprecedented in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not serve as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and to show what it can offer citizens.
